        overview_fact_kicker: "Officially verified today",
        overview_fact_title: "Today's updates",
        overview_fact_date_prefix: "Updated on",
        overview_fact_1_title: "Model recommendations aligned to surfaces",
        overview_fact_1_desc: "Re-checking `codex/models` confirms that `gpt-5.5` is still the top recommendation. Start there when it appears in the Codex model picker, and use `gpt-5.4` when it has not rolled out to the account yet. One important clarification is now explicit in the guide: inside Codex, `gpt-5.5` is currently available only when you sign in with ChatGPT, not with API-key authentication. In the API itself, the official Models docs list both `gpt-5.5` and `gpt-5.5-pro`. `gpt-5.4-mini` stays the fast local/subagent option, Codex Cloud still belongs to the `gpt-5.3-codex` path, and `gpt-5.2` remains the main alternative model.",
        overview_fact_2_title: "GPT-5.5 promoted, GPT-5.4 remains important",
        overview_fact_2_desc: "The latest model story is now split more clearly. `gpt-5.5` is the top recommendation for complex coding, computer use, knowledge work, and research workflows in Codex. In the API, regular `gpt-5.5` and higher-accuracy `gpt-5.5-pro` are separate models, with GPT-5.5 pro available for Responses API requests including Batch API. `gpt-5.4` still matters for rollout, cost, or latency tradeoffs, while `gpt-5.4-mini` remains the efficient choice for lighter work and subagents.",
        overview_fact_3_title: "Plans and team pricing clarified",
        overview_fact_3_desc: "Quickstart still says every ChatGPT plan includes Codex. The current `codex/pricing` page keeps the `GPT-5.5` usage tables and published local-message ranges (`gpt-5.5` 15-80, `gpt-5.4` 20-100, `gpt-5.4-mini` 60-350, `gpt-5.3-codex` 30-150 on Plus), while stating that token-based credit tables currently apply to new/existing Business customers and new Enterprise customers first. Other plan types should still read the previous message-based card until they are migrated. The current Pro promos also run through May 31, 2026. API pricing and limits should be checked separately for `gpt-5.5` and `gpt-5.5-pro`.",
        overview_fact_4_title: "IDE and Windows paths clarified",
        overview_fact_4_desc: "The IDE docs now cover both VS Code-style editors and JetBrains across macOS, Windows, and Linux. The practical guidance is still that Windows agent mode is most reliable inside a WSL2 workspace, while the Windows docs now more clearly separate Microsoft Store / `winget` installation, `elevated` vs `unelevated` sandboxing, private-desktop defaults, and the choice between native Windows performance and a Linux-native WSL2 toolchain.",
        overview_fact_5_title: "App workflows reflected",
        overview_fact_5_desc: "Cross-checking `Introducing the Codex app`, the April 16 `Codex for (almost) everything` post, and the current `app/features` / `app/automations` docs helped move worktrees, built-in Git, the integrated terminal, skills, automations, thread automations, chats, the in-app browser, artifact preview, image generation, background computer use, broader plugins, multiple terminal tabs, SSH devboxes, and the summary pane earlier in the guide.",
        overview_fact_6_title: "Config/plugins/security refreshed",
        overview_fact_6_desc: "The guide now keeps `review_model`, granular approvals, `approvals_reviewer`, top-level `web_search`, `tools.web_search`, `tools.view_image`, `service_tier`, `personality`, `default_permissions`, Windows sandbox keys, `model_instructions_file`, `memories.disable_on_external_context`, protected paths, JSON schema, app-connector controls, feature flags, permissions profiles, plugin packaging, and the split cloud runtime aligned with current docs.",
