        changelog_kicker: "Changelog",
        changelog_title: "Today's Updates",
        changelog_item_1: "Reconfirmed `gpt-5.5` as the top recommendation, added the ChatGPT-login-only note for Codex, and kept `gpt-5.5-pro` on the API side.",
        changelog_item_2: "Updated pricing to the current Plus / Pro 5x / Pro 20x / Business / API Key reading path and separated message limits from token-credit tables.",
        changelog_item_3: "Rechecked Quickstart, IDE, and Windows docs so the App-first path, JetBrains support, and WSL2 guidance read more clearly.",
        changelog_item_4: "Refreshed the App section against `Codex for (almost) everything`, including browser use, computer use, plugins, terminal tabs, SSH devboxes, and artifact/sidebar flows.",
        changelog_item_5: "Revalidated Docs MCP, best practices, config, plugins, and skills guidance so AGENTS.md, config keys, and repeatable-work advice stay current.",
        changelog_sources_toggle: "How sources are placed",
        changelog_sources_note: "Instead of keeping one long source dump at the bottom, the guide now points you to the small `Sources` line under each section. The changelog should stay short, while the relevant section holds the links you are most likely to verify next.",
        s1_title: "Codex Ecosystem Overview",
        s1_intro: "OpenAI Codex is a coding agent for software development. In plain terms, it is closer to a coding teammate that can read code, make changes, run checks, and help you finish tasks than to a simple autocomplete tool. The latest official docs describe Codex across the app, IDEs, the CLI, web/iOS surfaces, and SDK-driven automation, and now recommend starting with `gpt-5.5` when it appears in your model picker. One important current constraint is that inside Codex, `gpt-5.5` is available only when you sign in with ChatGPT, not with API-key authentication. In the API, the official Models docs list `gpt-5.5`, and `gpt-5.5-pro` is available for Responses API requests including Batch API. Use `gpt-5.4-mini` for fast local or subagent work, `gpt-5.3-codex` for Codex Cloud and code review, and `gpt-5.2` as the main alternative model.",
        s1_philosophy: '"From code generation → software engineer teammate"',
        s1_desc: "So the practical difference is scope: instead of suggesting one line at a time, Codex can look across files, make changes, run tests, and narrow down what broke while you review the result.",
